00:55:29,481 --> 00:55:31,223
we've shown earlier and now we

1411
00:55:31,223 --> 00:55:32,804
have started to get further

1412
00:55:32,804 --> 00:55:37,128
down this pyramid after having

1413
00:55:37,128 --> 00:55:38,750
talked a bit about the structure now

1414
00:55:38,750 --> 00:55:41,373
if you have a project

1415
00:55:41,373 --> 00:55:44,736
that you have something that you

1416
00:55:44,736 --> 00:55:50,061
need to need to do like having a workflow

1417
00:55:50,061 --> 00:55:51,904
This is something that also

1418
00:55:51,904 --> 00:55:53,688
needs to be reported and

1419
00:55:53,688 --> 00:55:55,230
very often this reported in scripts,

1420
00:55:56,052 --> 00:55:57,675
but it can also be reported

1421
00:55:57,675 --> 00:56:01,181
in other ways and depending on

1422
00:56:01,181 --> 00:56:04,507
what you have it's like or

1423
00:56:04,507 --> 00:56:07,172
more easily or more difficult to reproduce.

1424
00:56:10,097 --> 00:56:10,398
So.

1425
00:56:11,914 --> 00:56:13,477
There are commonly a couple

1426
00:56:13,477 --> 00:56:16,483
of steps from input data that

1427
00:56:16,483 --> 00:56:18,266
you have from experiments or

1428
00:56:18,266 --> 00:56:20,671
from other sources to the results

1429
00:56:20,671 --> 00:56:22,956
that you want to present for a paper.

1430
00:56:23,938 --> 00:56:27,745
And we are using an example

1431
00:56:27,745 --> 00:56:30,831
project that is essentially just word counting.

1432
00:56:30,831 --> 00:56:33,356
And even in this very simple thing

1433
00:56:33,356 --> 00:56:34,858
where we want to count

1434
00:56:34,858 --> 00:56:36,982
words and create some statistics

1435
00:56:36,982 --> 00:56:41,050
for the amount of words that

1436
00:56:41,050 --> 00:56:46,019
are occurring in some books, it

1437
00:56:46,019 --> 00:56:46,860
has a couple of steps.

1438
00:56:46,860 --> 00:56:48,283
So we first have to

1439
00:56:48,283 --> 00:56:51,228
analyze the frequencies of the words.

1440
00:56:51,228 --> 00:56:53,953
That's done in a counterpy file.

1441
00:56:55,165 --> 00:56:56,807
for all the books that

1442
00:56:56,807 --> 00:56:57,889
we currently have, which is

1443
00:56:59,211 --> 00:57:01,554
in this data directory.

1444
00:57:01,554 --> 00:57:04,799
So data directory currently

1445
00:57:04,799 --> 00:57:06,882
contains these four books and

1446
00:57:06,882 --> 00:57:09,065
the books essentially just contain

1447
00:57:09,065 --> 00:57:11,248
the plain text of these books

1448
00:57:11,248 --> 00:57:14,453
that we are investigating here.

1449
00:57:14,453 --> 00:57:17,339
And the counterpy file simply says

1450
00:57:17,339 --> 00:57:21,367
that we are checking how

1451
00:57:21,367 --> 00:57:28,040
often does a certain word occur in this book.

1452
00:57:29,843 --> 00:57:31,746
And then we want to plot them

1453
00:57:31,746 --> 00:57:34,371
and generate these nice plots

1454
00:57:34,371 --> 00:57:35,714
so that we can put into our paper.

1455
00:57:36,635 --> 00:57:38,859
And for a single book,

1456
00:57:38,859 --> 00:57:40,763
this is essentially what we would be doing.

1457
00:57:40,763 --> 00:57:44,249
So I have this in here.

1458
00:57:44,249 --> 00:57:48,356
I'm creating this counter pi,

1459
00:57:48,356 --> 00:57:50,520
and then I have a aisles.data

1460
00:57:50,520 --> 00:57:52,644
that I can have a look at.

1461
00:57:55,645 --> 00:57:56,766
How does this look like?

1462
00:57:56,766 --> 00:57:59,109
So yeah, this is the off and O

1463
00:57:59,109 --> 00:58:00,711
and two, and then I

1464
00:58:00,711 --> 00:58:07,558
can plot this relatively easily and

1465
00:58:07,558 --> 00:58:14,506
can get a file that is

1466
00:58:14,506 --> 00:58:16,328
essentially showing this plot.

1467
00:58:19,972 --> 00:58:20,893
Let's see.

1468
00:58:27,420 --> 00:58:29,323
My machine being slow.

1469
00:58:29,323 --> 00:58:31,687
But yeah, I get this file.

1470
00:58:31,687 --> 00:58:34,973
And this is all nice and well,

1471
00:58:34,973 --> 00:58:36,636
but now if we imagine that

1472
00:58:37,558 --> 00:58:38,980
we have to repeat this

1473
00:58:38,980 --> 00:58:40,282
multiple times, that would

1474
00:58:40,282 --> 00:58:45,291
essentially happen in our run all, which is...

1475
00:58:45,291 --> 00:58:50,096
a script that essentially just

1476
00:58:50,096 --> 00:58:51,878
says okay for the first file

1477
00:58:51,878 --> 00:58:53,800
for the first file for the second file

1478
00:58:53,800 --> 00:58:56,543
for the third file for the fourth file

1479
00:58:57,364 --> 00:58:59,226
and yeah this is this works

1480
00:58:59,226 --> 00:59:00,448
for the four books that we have

1481
00:59:00,448 --> 00:59:02,050
but if we want to have 500

1482
00:59:02,050 --> 00:59:04,813
books now this script

1483
00:59:04,813 --> 00:59:08,022
becomes essentially unmaintainable

1484
00:59:08,022 --> 00:59:09,104
because there are so many

1485
00:59:09,104 --> 00:59:11,931
different files now and there is

1486
00:59:11,931 --> 00:59:15,118
so likely to be some kind of typo or whatever.

1487
00:59:15,118 --> 00:59:16,200
We can of course create

1488
00:59:16,200 --> 00:59:20,389
this file automatically and stuff,

1489
00:59:20,389 --> 00:59:25,639
but it's just getting more and more crowded.

1490
00:59:25,639 --> 00:59:28,544
I think maybe one thing is

1491
00:59:28,544 --> 00:59:30,248
that quite many people would

1492
00:59:30,248 --> 00:59:32,071
actually execute those steps

1493
00:59:32,071 --> 00:59:33,634
manually, then it's very easy

1494
00:59:33,634 --> 00:59:34,796
to forget something.

1495
00:59:34,796 --> 00:59:37,821
So already the script is one

1496
00:59:37,821 --> 00:59:40,066
step towards a certain degree

1497
00:59:40,066 --> 00:59:42,430
of reproducibility that I think

1498
00:59:42,430 --> 00:59:44,553
It's important to recognize here

1499
00:59:44,553 --> 00:59:46,696
that having a script that makes sure

1500
00:59:46,696 --> 00:59:49,420
that it's actually executed in

1501
00:59:49,420 --> 00:59:52,024
order for everything is not a

1502
00:59:52,024 --> 00:59:53,046
bad thing per se.

1503
00:59:53,046 --> 00:59:55,369
That's already a good starting point.

1504
00:59:55,369 --> 00:59:57,152
So better than doing it by hand

1505
00:59:57,152 --> 00:59:58,194
and forgetting half of

1506
00:59:58,194 --> 01:00:01,178
the books, especially if you get 500.

1507
01:00:01,178 --> 01:00:03,062
Yeah, that definitely.

1508
01:00:03,062 --> 01:00:05,206
But it just, even if you

1509
01:00:05,206 --> 01:00:07,951
do it in the script, it becomes unmaintainable.

1510
01:00:07,951 --> 01:00:09,855
So this is something that you can do

1511
01:00:09,855 --> 01:00:12,040
for a few things and for

1512
01:00:12,040 --> 01:00:14,805
a quite simplistic workflow where

1513
01:00:14,805 --> 01:00:17,571
you have some fixed input data

1514
01:00:17,571 --> 01:00:20,116
and some fixed output data, that's okay.

1515
01:00:20,116 --> 01:00:21,799
That's perfectly fine.

1516
01:00:21,799 --> 01:00:24,242
But as soon as you start to, for example,

1517
01:00:24,242 --> 01:00:25,904
collect more and more data over time

1518
01:00:25,904 --> 01:00:27,225
and you need to run this again

1519
01:00:27,225 --> 01:00:29,748
and again and again for new things

1520
01:00:29,748 --> 01:00:31,450
that are coming in, you

1521
01:00:31,450 --> 01:00:32,751
commonly don't want to run

1522
01:00:32,751 --> 01:00:34,954
everything again because, yeah, in

1523
01:00:34,954 --> 01:00:36,956
this case, the computation takes

1524
01:00:36,956 --> 01:00:38,297
a second or something.

1525
01:00:38,297 --> 01:00:39,859
But let's assume that each

1526
01:00:41,261 --> 01:00:44,104
calculation here or each individual

1527
01:00:44,104 --> 01:00:47,888
data entry takes an hour or two.

1528
01:00:47,888 --> 01:00:49,571
you don't want to rerun this

1529
01:00:49,571 --> 01:00:51,815
all the time if nothing has changed

1530
01:00:52,997 --> 01:00:56,082
and one more thing to mention here is

1531
01:00:56,082 --> 01:00:58,185
that this kind of stating

1532
01:00:58,185 --> 01:01:00,649
every individual element is

1533
01:01:00,649 --> 01:01:02,392
also called imperative style where

1534
01:01:02,392 --> 01:01:05,577
you tell a script every single

1535
01:01:05,577 --> 01:01:10,706
thing that it has to do one after another and

1536
01:01:11,648 --> 01:01:13,612
Well, there are some advantages

1537
01:01:13,612 --> 01:01:15,355
to this solution compared to

1538
01:01:15,355 --> 01:01:18,841
processing all one by one.

1539
01:01:18,841 --> 01:01:24,913
And yeah, as Ninash already

1540
01:01:24,913 --> 01:01:28,945
mentioned, this run all is

1541
01:01:28,945 --> 01:01:30,930
better reproducible, because you're

1542
01:01:30,930 --> 01:01:32,654
not forgetting one or the other.

1543
01:01:32,654 --> 01:01:35,881
So having this in a script,

1544
01:01:35,881 --> 01:01:38,287
yeah, is the first step.

1545
01:01:38,287 --> 01:01:40,573
But as I said, if we have more

1546
01:01:40,573 --> 01:01:41,956
and more things coming in,

1547
01:01:41,956 --> 01:01:45,384
then there start to be more and more problems.

1548
01:01:46,832 --> 01:01:49,501
And that's where workflow tools come in.

1549
01:01:49,501 --> 01:01:51,507
So workflow tools are

1550
01:01:51,507 --> 01:01:53,132
essentially tools that help you

1551
01:01:53,132 --> 01:01:56,202
to organize workflows that you have

1552
01:01:56,202 --> 01:01:58,389
to do in a repetitive fashion

1553
01:01:58,389 --> 01:02:01,007
or that are more complex.

1554
01:02:01,007 --> 01:02:04,052
And we will focus here on SnakeMake,

1555
01:02:04,052 --> 01:02:05,074
but there are multiple

1556
01:02:05,074 --> 01:02:06,416
different other tools that are

1557
01:02:06,416 --> 01:02:07,458
also mentioned later on.

1558
01:02:08,700 --> 01:02:11,345
And SnakeMake, in contrast

1559
01:02:13,689 --> 01:02:17,195
to this imperative style,

1560
01:02:17,195 --> 01:02:20,220
uses something that's called

1561
01:02:20,220 --> 01:02:22,624
a declarative style, sorry.

1562
01:02:22,624 --> 01:02:25,027
And this will also be

1563
01:02:25,027 --> 01:02:26,850
the exercise, will also be used

1564
01:02:26,850 --> 01:02:30,114
in the exercise that you're going

1565
01:02:30,114 --> 01:02:31,256
to be doing soonish.

1566
01:02:31,256 --> 01:02:34,020
But I quickly go over how

1567
01:02:34,020 --> 01:02:38,446
this snake make or how snake make works.

1568
01:02:38,446 --> 01:02:41,951
So in snake make, you

1569
01:02:41,951 --> 01:02:45,575
define rules and snake make

1570
01:02:45,575 --> 01:02:48,159
tries to satisfy all rules.

1571
01:02:49,489 --> 01:02:51,114
And that means that a rule

1572
01:02:51,114 --> 01:02:54,543
or to satisfy a rule, all the

1573
01:02:54,543 --> 01:02:56,429
inputs of the rule have to

1574
01:02:56,429 --> 01:02:58,254
be created or satisfied.

1575
01:02:59,698 --> 01:03:04,339
And in our bookcase, the rule

1576
01:03:04,339 --> 01:03:07,303
the one rule to rule them all,

1577
01:03:08,285 --> 01:03:09,867
that is essentially indicating, okay,

1578
01:03:09,867 --> 01:03:12,310
this is the final rule, the final rule,

1579
01:03:12,310 --> 01:03:16,116
or this is the target requires

1580
01:03:16,116 --> 01:03:17,618
as inputs, you could also

1581
01:03:17,618 --> 01:03:20,642
call inputs requirements for

1582
01:03:20,642 --> 01:03:24,348
this, that everything in statistics

1583
01:03:25,169 --> 01:03:28,774
book data exists and

1584
01:03:28,774 --> 01:03:31,038
the book here will be

1585
01:03:31,038 --> 01:03:36,327
replaced by whatever is in the data array.

1586
01:03:36,327 --> 01:03:37,329
So this is somewhat of

1587
01:03:37,329 --> 01:03:40,294
a Pythonic syntax that you can

1588
01:03:40,294 --> 01:03:43,340
use Python code in the snake files.

1589
01:03:44,402 --> 01:03:48,298
And this data is generated by looking

1590
01:03:48,298 --> 01:03:49,923
through the data folder,

1591
01:03:49,923 --> 01:03:51,327
through everything that matches

1592
01:03:51,327 --> 01:03:55,519
this placeholder.txt, and then

1593
01:03:55,519 --> 01:04:01,818
saying, okay, this becomes the data book,

1594
01:04:02,997 --> 01:04:06,642
or no, this is the book field of this

1595
01:04:06,642 --> 01:04:09,345
and this glob wildcards

1596
01:04:09,345 --> 01:04:11,728
generates these book fields for

1597
01:04:11,728 --> 01:04:13,991
all elements in here.

1598
01:04:15,093 --> 01:04:17,576
So for the rule all, we

1599
01:04:17,576 --> 01:04:20,099
want everything in the statistics

1600
01:04:20,099 --> 01:04:22,222
book data to exist and we

1601
01:04:22,222 --> 01:04:25,606
want everything in the book PNG

1602
01:04:25,606 --> 01:04:29,912
to exist and they have to be

1603
01:04:29,912 --> 01:04:32,736
as recent as any requirements

1604
01:04:32,736 --> 01:04:36,120
that or in each rule it

1605
01:04:36,120 --> 01:04:38,103
will be checked whether there

1606
01:04:38,103 --> 01:04:40,286
have been updates in the inputs

1607
01:04:40,286 --> 01:04:42,589
and then the rule has to be executed

1608
01:04:43,430 --> 01:04:45,733
and for example count words

1609
01:04:45,733 --> 01:04:49,018
here requires as an input the

1610
01:04:49,018 --> 01:04:51,261
count.py so your script file so

1611
01:04:51,261 --> 01:04:52,963
if you change your script

1612
01:04:52,963 --> 01:04:54,144
you will have to rerun

1613
01:04:54,144 --> 01:04:56,867
this for all elements and

1614
01:04:56,867 --> 01:04:58,790
it requires the different book files.

1615
01:04:58,790 --> 01:05:01,473
So if one of the book files changes

1616
01:05:01,473 --> 01:05:05,177
or there's a new book file,

1617
01:05:05,177 --> 01:05:06,519
then it has to generate this

1618
01:05:06,519 --> 01:05:07,560
for the new book file.

1619
01:05:08,721 --> 01:05:11,484
And the output from this is

1620
01:05:11,484 --> 01:05:15,128
defined as this is the statistics file data.

1621
01:05:15,128 --> 01:05:20,034
So this essentially satisfies this input.

1622
01:05:21,516 --> 01:05:23,479
And so it will look up

1623
01:05:23,479 --> 01:05:25,662
in the underlying rules what

1624
01:05:25,662 --> 01:05:29,348
rules could satisfy one of my

1625
01:05:29,348 --> 01:05:32,112
inputs or one of my requirements.

1626
01:05:32,112 --> 01:05:33,574
And then there is the command

1627
01:05:33,574 --> 01:05:35,237
that is being called when

1628
01:05:35,237 --> 01:05:37,039
this rule is being executed.

1629
01:05:38,161 --> 01:05:39,343
And that's essentially just, in

1630
01:05:39,343 --> 01:05:40,504
this case, a Python command.

1631
01:05:40,504 --> 01:05:42,247
This could be anything else.

1632
01:05:42,247 --> 01:05:43,449
This could also be R,

1633
01:05:43,449 --> 01:05:46,493
MATLAB, or whatever language you want.

1634
01:05:47,315 --> 01:05:48,857
SnakeMate doesn't make a difference here.

1635
01:05:50,153 --> 01:05:52,718
And it essentially says, okay, well,

1636
01:05:54,240 --> 01:05:57,326
for each input, the input.script

1637
01:05:57,326 --> 01:05:59,430
value is being used, and

1638
01:05:59,430 --> 01:06:01,794
that's the code count.py.

1639
01:06:02,756 --> 01:06:05,921
And the input.book, that's the data,

1640
01:06:05,921 --> 01:06:07,584
whatever the file is that

1641
01:06:07,584 --> 01:06:10,289
came from that, again, comes

1642
01:06:10,289 --> 01:06:12,630
from the requirement here.

1643
01:06:12,630 --> 01:06:15,294
and is passed kind of downwards.

1644
01:06:15,294 --> 01:06:17,437
And this generates the output,

1645
01:06:18,940 --> 01:06:21,023
which is again for each file.

1646
01:06:22,105 --> 01:06:23,306
And this is how SnakeMake

1647
01:06:24,248 --> 01:06:27,853
builds these rules and goes

1648
01:06:27,853 --> 01:06:30,357
through the graph and essentially checks

1649
01:06:30,357 --> 01:06:32,280
for every input if it

1650
01:06:32,280 --> 01:06:37,167
changed and then generates the outputs.

1651
01:06:37,167 --> 01:06:38,529
We'll also check whether

1652
01:06:38,529 --> 01:06:40,712
the outputs changed if there

1653
01:06:40,712 --> 01:06:42,736
are dependencies because the make

1654
01:06:42,736 --> 01:06:44,298
plot then depends on the outputs

1655
01:06:44,298 --> 01:06:46,141
of the count words and so on.

1656
01:06:48,064 --> 01:06:49,706
I think this is going to

1657
01:06:49,706 --> 01:06:52,951
